<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
     NARRATIVE — Sectioned, not a wall of text
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="sp-narrative">
  <div class="sp-narrative-inner">

    <div class="sp-narrative-block reveal">
      <h2 class="sp-narrative-heading">THE BEGINNING</h2>
      <p>When I joined SadaPay in December 2020, there was no app, no design team, and no design system. Just a bold idea — build Pakistan's first neobank — and a CEO who believed design would be the difference.</p>
      <p>I was the founding designer. The first screen, the first flow, the first pixel — all mine. Within months, I'd designed the entire mobile banking experience from scratch: onboarding, KYC, wallets, transfers, bill payments, and card management.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="sp-narrative-block reveal">
      <h2 class="sp-narrative-heading">THE BREAKOUT</h2>
      <p><strong>The waitlist changed everything.</strong> 700,000 people signed up with zero paid acquisition. I designed a gamification system — Founders Club cards, golden tickets, branded merchandise, a referral engine. Celebrities felt FOMO. Irfan Junejo came to the office. It was the first time a Pakistani fintech had created genuine cultural hype.</p>
      <p>I designed Pakistan's first numberless debit card with Mastercard — the first of its kind in the MEA region. Security through simplicity instead of complexity.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="sp-narrative-block reveal">
      <h2 class="sp-narrative-heading">THE TEAM</h2>
      <p>I hired 15-20 designers over my tenure, managing a core team of 8 at peak. Associates straight from university with messy portfolios — I saw something in them. The joke in Pakistan's design community became: <em>"Getting into Harvard is easier than getting into SadaPay's design team."</em></p>
      <p>Those designers are now leading teams at Revolut London and companies across the world.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="sp-narrative-block reveal">
      <h2 class="sp-narrative-heading">CHALLENGING ASSUMPTIONS</h2>
      <p>I don't accept "that's just how it works" as an answer. I challenged unnecessary PINs and OTPs in the authentication flow, introduced biometric-only login, put emojis in a banking app — a first in Pakistan — and proposed QR code payments years before the industry adopted it.</p>
      <p>I built service design blueprints that mapped every touchpoint in the system. The CEO called this my "superpower" — they helped reduce fraud by making invisible flows visible.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="sp-narrative-block reveal">
      <h2 class="sp-narrative-heading">THE EXIT</h2>
      <p>SadaPay helped raise $7.2M pre-seed (the largest by a Pakistani startup at the time), followed by seed and Series A — totaling $20M+. The design was a selling point in every investor deck. In 2024, Papara acquired SadaPay for $50M.</p>
      <p>I was laid off post-acquisition. Zero compensation. Stocks worth nothing. But SadaPay changed Pakistan's fintech landscape permanently — every bank revamped their app after us.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

